WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Hi, and welcome to our fifth Enterprise Community Meetup,

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.000
where we'll discuss another end-to-end data science workflow using Posit Team.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.000
My name is Ryan Johnson, and I'm a data science advisor here at Posit.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Now, for today's session, we're going to do things a little bit differently,

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:22.000
and rather than discuss a single end-to-end data science workflow,

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
we're actually going to break it up into a series of smaller workflows

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:31.000
using one of my favorite packages in both R and Python called Pins.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Now, during today's session, we'll start off with a brief introduction into Posit Team,

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
and then we'll talk about how Posit Team, specifically Posit Connect,

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
can be used to enhance your Pins workflows.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:49.000
So with that, let's go ahead and get started with an introduction to Posit Team.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.000
All right, if you joined us in the past months,

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:54.000
then you've probably seen this diagram before.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.000
This is a quick overview of Posit Team,

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
and we'll start right up here at the very top with your data scientists,

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.000
your data analysts, your end users.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
And they will be creating insights using Posit Workbench.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:11.000
This is a development environment, and they can develop within RStudio,

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:16.000
Jupyter, or VS Code, creating things in both R and Python.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
So if you're R developers, maybe they're creating Shiny applications,

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Quarto documents, Plumber APIs.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
Or if you have Python developers, maybe they're creating applications

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:30.000
using things like Bokeh or Dash, Streamlip.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
You can have Jupyter Notebooks as well, Shiny for Python, Pins for Python,

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.000
which we'll talk about in a bit here.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
But it doesn't do the data scientists any good

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
if they can't share that content with the people that need to see it.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.000
That could be their coworkers, it could be their boss,

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.000
or maybe just their friends and family.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
And that's where Posit Connect comes into play.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.000
Connect is our professional publishing platform

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.000
and allows you to easily share those insights with whoever you want.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.000
And then finally, we have Posit Package Manager,

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.000
which does exactly as its name implies,

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:09.000
helps control all those great open source packages in both R and Python.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:14.000
And you can also host and share any internally developed R and Python packages

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
with your team as well.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Now, for today's workflow, we're going to focus on Pins.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:26.000
And in a second, I'll explain what the Pins package is and how you use it,

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.000
but I thought it might be helpful to first describe a few scenarios

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:35.000
where you might want to consider using the Pins package for your workflows.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
In this first scenario, have you ever created an asset,

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:40.000
maybe like a piece of data,

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
that you thought was the final version of the data,

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.000
but then you had to go back and make some edits

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:48.000
and create another final version.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
And rather than overwriting the original data set,

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.000
you decide to give it a new name.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.000
And maybe you go through this process again and again and again,

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:01.000
and you end up with multiple final versions of a data set,

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.000
and no one knows what the true final version is.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Maybe this data we just talked about is used by many different content types,

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:15.000
including a shiny app in R or a Korto document in Python,

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.000
and you're worried that the data may not be consistent across all assets.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
Additionally, maybe you want to share this data with multiple people,

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:29.000
and it's typically much easier and safer to share a Pin

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:32.000
rather than trying to email files around.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And finally, maybe this data contains sensitive information,

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.000
and you only want to share it with specific people or groups of people.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And this is actually possible when using pins in combination with PositConnect.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
So how do pins actually work?

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:54.000
The best way to think of pins, in my opinion, is to think of a corkboard.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Similar to how you can pin a note to a corkboard,

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:01.000
you can pin an R or Python object to a board

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
where you and others can access it.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.000
To further explain this corkboard analogy,

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
the pushpin is the tool we use to pin an object to the corkboard.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
This is the pins package.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
The note that we pin is our R or Python object,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.000
and this could be a dataset, a model, plots, or even files.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.000
Finally, the corkboard in our workflows for today will be PositConnect.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Now, there are a lot of other boards you could use,

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.000
including Amazon S3, Azure, or Google Cloud Storage,

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.000
or even local or shared folders.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:40.000
But PositConnect does come with some added advantages,

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:42.000
which we'll discuss today.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Before we get started with pins,

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
we need to do a small amount of prep work.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
And since we are going to show some workflows in both R and Python,

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
we'll first need to install the pins package in both languages,

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
and then we'll need to connect to our board,

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:00.000
which again will be PositConnect.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
So let's do that now, and we'll start with R in our studio.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
So here I am within Posit Workbench,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
